        output='The MD&A shows the AI segment is in a heavy infrastructure build‑out phase, with capital expenditures dramatically outpacing revenue. Management characterizes the segment as an early‑stage, high‑investment business prioritizing growth over near‑term profitability.\n\n---\n\n### 1. AI Infrastructure Build‑out and Data Center Investments\n\n**Liquidity and Capital Resources section**  \nThe year‑over‑year increase in net cash used in investing activities is *“primarily driven by an increase in capital expenditures of $6,748 million related to the build out of data centers and related infrastructure.”* Financing cash flows surged largely due to *“an increase in proceeds from debt and other financing arrangements for our AI segment of $16,055 million”*—funding raised specifically to support that infrastructure build‑out (via the SpaceX Bridge Loan and equity sales).\n\n**Capital expenditure detail by segment**  \nAI‑specific capex figures show a rapid, multi‑year acceleration:\n\n| Period | AI Capex | \n|--------|----------|\n| Q1’26 (unaudited) | $7,723 million |\n| Q1’25 (unaudited) | $2,567 million |\n| FY2025 | $12,727 million |\n| FY2024 | $5,633 million |\n| FY2023 | $463 million |\n\nThe MD&A explains the Q1’26 increase was *“primarily driven by investments in the rapid expansion of our terrestrial data centers, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure.”* This language signals that data center construction—not just equipment purchases—is the core use of capital.\n\n**Balance sheet note**  \nConstruction‑in‑progress, the largest PP&E category, is *“primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service.”* This confirms a massive pipeline of un‑depreciated assets yet to come online.\n\n**Strategic rationale**  \nThe preamble underscores why this build‑out is occurring: *“Frontier AI has become fundamentally infrastructure‑constrained. … Compute infrastructure scale helps determine model iteration speed, model quality, and capital efficiency—making infrastructure itself a critical capability.”* Management is betting that owning massive GPU clusters and purpose‑built data centers will be a competitive moat.\n\n---\n\n### 2. AI Capex Relative to Revenue\n\nThe ratio of capex to revenue highlights how early the investment cycle is:\n\n| Metric | Q1’26 | FY2025 | FY2024 |\n|--------|-------|--------|--------|\n| AI segment revenue | $818 M | $3,201 M | N/A (segment not separated) |\n| AI segment capex | $7,723 M | $12,727 M | $5,633 M |\n| Capex / Revenue | ~9.4x | ~4.0x | N/A |\n\nRevenue is a fraction of the capital being deployed. The AI segment remains deeply unprofitable: for Q1’26, it reported a loss from operations of $(2,469) million and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $(609) million. For FY2025, it lost $(6,355) million from operations with $(1,237) million in Segment Adjusted EBITDA. The MD&A directly ties these losses to the build‑out: *“AI loss from operations … increased … primarily driven by higher cloud computing and GPU depreciation costs, data center infrastructure and employee expenses, partially offset by higher revenue.”*\n\nThe **Risk Factors** section explicitly frames the timeline: *“we plan to allocate substantial capital to build our AI compute infrastructure, and we expect a multi‑year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA.”* This is not a short‑term inflection; management is projecting years of heavy capex before the segment reaches sustained profitability.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Management’s Characterization of the AI Segment’s Growth Phase\n\nManagement uses clear language to describe the AI segment’s stage:\n\n* **“Earlier stage of development”** – The segment overview states that the FY2025 losses reflect its *“earlier stage of development and continued investments to support long‑term growth opportunities in AI.”*\n* **Growth‑over‑profit posture** – *“In our newly acquired AI segment, we plan to prioritize growth and investment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure.”*\n* **Rapid scaling narrative** – The SG&A discussion notes higher employee costs *“as our AI business grew rapidly”* and R&D expenses are driven by *“depreciation of GPU hardware and the cost of cloud computing as a result of our AI data center expansions.”*\n* **Future operating leverage expectation** – While AI cost of revenue will rise in absolute dollars, management expects it *“to decrease as a percentage of revenue as we monetize our products and as we expand our service offerings.”* This signals that the current high‑cost structure is a temporary feature of the investment phase.\n* **Persistent losses acknowledged** – The Risk Factors warn that the AI segment *“has incurred significant operating losses since inception, and we may not achieve profitability in this segment, or, if achieved, sustain it.”*\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\nThe MD&A paints a picture of an AI segment in the midst of an unprecedented infrastructure build‑out. Data center construction and GPU deployments are the primary drivers of investing cash flows, financed by large‑scale debt and equity raises. Capex dwarfs revenue by multiples, and operating losses are widening as depreciation and facility costs mount. Management portrays this as the natural “earlier stage” of a long‑term growth bet, with a multi‑year runway before the segment can generate sustained positive Adjusted EBITDA. The emphasis throughout is on capturing a massive AI opportunity, even at the expense of near‑term profitability.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=48.645,
