        output='The S-1 describes the Connectivity segment’s capital intensity and investment cycle as evolving from an early, externally funded build‑out phase to a more mature, self‑sustaining stage—while still investing meaningfully in network expansion.  \n\n**Early build‑out phase (historical funding model)**  \n- The company “invested in our Connectivity segment as we generated Segment Adjusted EBITDA from our Space segment, along with additional equity capital that we raised externally.”  \n- This capital funded the initial deployment of the Starlink satellite constellation, creating a segment that now generates “predictable and recurring revenue.”  \n\n**Transition to maturity and sustained profitability**  \n- The Connectivity segment “became in aggregate Segment Adjusted EBITDA positive on a sustained basis beginning in 2023,” marking a key inflection point.  \n- By 2025, the segment generated **$4,423 million** in income from operations and **$7,168 million** in Segment Adjusted EBITDA, with revenue of **$11,387 million** (up 49.8% YoY). This demonstrates that the business is now highly profitable and capable of self‑funding further investments.\n\n**How capex trend evolved (capital intensity)**  \nAbsolute capital expenditure continued to increase each year, but the pace of growth relative to revenue moderated, reflecting declining capital intensity as the network scaled:\n\n| Year | Connectivity Capex | YoY Change | Revenue (for reference) | Capex as % of Revenue |\n|------|-------------------|------------|--------------------------|------------------------|\n| 2023 | $2,455\u202fM          | –          | Not separately stated*   | –                      |\n| 2024 | $3,498\u202fM          | +$1,043\u202fM  | $7,599\u202fM                 | ~46%                   |\n| 2025 | $4,178\u202fM          | +$680\u202fM    | $11,387\u202fM                | ~37%                   |\n| Q1 2025 | $814\u202fM        | –          | –                        | –                      |\n| Q1 2026 | $1,332\u202fM      | +$518\u202fM    | –                        | –                      |\n\n*Source: Capex data from MD&A; 2024 revenue from segment table; 2025 revenue from Preamble.*\n\n**Key takeaways from the S‑1**  \n- The year‑over‑year increases in capex were “primarily driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs as we continue to increase our number of satellites and grow our satellite network.”  \n- Even as capex rose, revenue grew much faster, causing **capex as a percentage of revenue to fall**—from about 46% in 2024 to 37% in 2025—indicating that the network’s capital intensity is declining in its more mature state.  \n- The company acknowledges that it will “continue to invest meaningfully” in Starlink’s infrastructure, but today those investments are supported by strong internal cash flows rather than the heavy reliance on external capital that characterized the early build‑out.  \n\nIn summary, the S-1 portrays the Connectivity capex trend as moving from a high‑intensity, externally funded deployment phase (pre‑2023) to a mature phase where the segment is solidly EBITDA‑positive, revenue is scaling rapidly, and capex—though still growing—represents a shrinking share of revenue, reflecting a more efficient, self‑reinforcing investment cycle.',
